[src:coinduction/coinduction] We will demonstrate how the *principle of induction* subsumes mathematical induction.
[src:coinduction/coinduction] Let P be some property of natural numbers.
[src:coinduction/coinduction] It should not be difficult to see that $\mu F=\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:coinduction/coinduction] Therefore, by the *principle of induction*, if we wish to prove some property P of $\mathbb {N}$ , it suffices to show that P is *F-closed*.
[src:coinduction/coinduction] This is precisely *mathematical induction* as stated.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] In computer science, **corecursion** is a type of operation that is dual to (structural) recursion.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Whereas recursion consumes a data structure by first handling the topmost layer before descending into its inner parts, corecursion produces a data structure by first defining the topmost layer before defining its inner parts.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Corecursion is a particularly important in total languages, as it allows encoding potentially non-terminating computations in a context where every function must terminate.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] It is supported by theorem provers Agda and Rocq.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Both corecursion and recursion can be thought of as operating on trees, which include data structures like lists and streams as special cases.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Since recursion must terminate, it only works on trees that are well-founded, i.e. not infinitely deep, which are called *data* or *initial data types*; on the other hand, corecursion produces *codata* or *final data types*, which includes infinitely deep trees.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Codata cannot be represented in memory directly, so is often implemented using self-referential data structures or lazy evaluation.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] This states that every natural number is either zero or the successor of an existing natural number.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] For example, the number one is represented as `Succ Zero`, two as `Succ (Succ Zero)`, three as `Succ (Succ (Succ Zero))` and so on.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] If we interpret the above declaration in an *inductive* way, then all natural numbers are generated like this, and we get our familiar set of natural numbers.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Note that the use of `repeat x n` is crucial—we could not have written `repeat x (Succ n)`, because that is the function we are trying to define, and therefore it would loop forever.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] More specifically, the input must get smaller—or rather deeper, if seen as a data structure—each time we recurse.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] `CoNat` has all the natural numbers that `Nat` has automatically.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] But because codata can be infinitely deep, it has an extra term `Succ (Succ (Succ (Succ …)))` that continues on indefinitely—often denoted ∞.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] While recursion requires that the input of the recursive call must get smaller each time, corecursion requires that the output of the recursive call must get larger each time.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] This is why we must write `Succ infinity`; just `infinity = infinity` would be disallowed as it loops forever.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] To illustrate the duality between recursion and corecursion, we can encapsulate them in two functions, `rec` and `corec`.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] These functions' existence, together with the regular two constructors of `Nat` and `CoNat`, uniquely identify their respective types, and therefore allow rewriting all forms of recursion and corecursion in terms of them.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Conceptually, `CoNat` can be thought of as a state machine, where `c` is a type encapsulating the "current state".
[src:coinduction/corecursion] The function `c -> Maybe c` is a state transition function that either results in termination with `Zero` or continuation with `Succ`.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] This example has many more infinitely deep terms that can only be constructed by corecursion.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] In a dependently-typed setting, codata can be encoded using M-types, which are dual to W-types.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Given a type *A* and an *A*-indexed family of types *B*, one can form the M-type ${\mathsf {M}}_{a:A}B(a)$ , representing the type of trees whose nodes are labelled with elements of *A* and who child nodes are indexed by the set *B*(*a*).
[src:coinduction/corecursion] M-types can be proven to exist in many elementary topoi, and their existence follows from the existence of W-types.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] The above section showed that there is an intimate link between natural and conatural numbers and `Maybe c`, and similarly between binary trees and `Either a (c, c)`.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] This link is made precise by showing that `Nat` is in bijection with `Maybe Nat`, and `CoNat` with `Maybe CoNat`; explicitly, this bjiection associates `Zero` with `Nothing` and `Succ n` with `Just n`.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] In other words, `Nat` and `CoNat` are fixed points (up to isomorphism) of the map $X\mapsto X+1$ .
[src:coinduction/corecursion] The difference between data and codata is that data is the least such fixed point, while codata is the greatest.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] In this way, recursion can be summarized as the statement that "every element of the type was generated only by the given constructors (`Zero` and `Succ` in the case of `Nat`/`CoNat`)", while corecursion states that "every value that can be analysed using the constructors as cases exists".
[src:coinduction/corecursion] From a category-theoretic perspective, `CoNat` can be precisely defined as the final coalgebra of the endofunctor $X\mapsto X+1$ .
[src:coinduction/corecursion] `Maybe c` can be replaced with any other functor in the above description to obtain the definition of any other coinductive type.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] For example, Cantor's theorem tells us that no set can be in bijection with its powerset, and therefore the powerset functor `a -> Bool` has no final coalgebra.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] However, in the case of polynomial functors or quotient polynomial functors, final coalgebras always exist; polynomial functors are functors that can be expressed in the form $\textstyle X\mapsto \sum _{a:\alpha }X^{\beta (a)}$ for a type *α* and *α*-indexed type family *β*(*a*).
[src:coinduction/corecursion] The M-type is exactly the construction of this final coalgebra.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] While one can reason about coinductive data types using the uniqueness of `corec` directly, it is often more convenient to use **coinduction**, which can prove equalities of codata.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Given a final coalgebra *A* of a polynomial functor *F*—i.e.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] The principle of coinduction states that for all bisimulations *R* on *A* and $(a,b)\in R$ , $a=b$ .
[src:coinduction/corecursion] where *π*₁ and *π*₂ are the first and second projection maps $R\rightarrow A$ .
[src:coinduction/corecursion] It can be seen this equivalent to the polynomial case by setting $f(a,b)=({\text{root}}(a),i\mapsto ({\text{branch}}(a,i),{\text{branch}}(b,i)))$ .
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Coinduction is easy to prove from the uniqueness of `corec`: *π*₁ and *π*₂ both satisfy the required property to be equal to `corec f`, and are therefore equal to each other, thus showing that $a=\pi _{1}(a,b)=\pi _{2}(a,b)=b$ .
[src:coinduction/corecursion] To demonstrate the usage of coinduction, we will prove some basic properties about addition on conatural numbers.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] This definition, while valid, hides some amount of complexity.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] We can prove that $a+0=a$ by coinduction on the relation $\{(a+0,a)|a\in \mathbb {N} ^{\infty }\}$ (where $\mathbb {N} ^{\infty }$ is the set of conatural numbers).
[src:coinduction/corecursion] First, it follows from the definition of addition that $a+0=0\iff a=0$ ; second, if we assume that $(x+1,y+1)$ is of the form $(a+0,a)$ for some *a*, we must show that $(x,y)$ is also of this form.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] If the domain of discourse is the category of sets and total functions (such as in theorem provers like Agda and Rocq), then final types (codata) may contain infinite, non-wellfounded values, whereas initial types (data) do not.
[src:coinduction/corecursion] Corecursion, referred to as *circular programming,* dates at least to (Bird 1984), who credits John Hughes and Philip Wadler; more general forms were developed in (Allison 1989).
[src:coinduction/corecursion] The original motivations included producing more efficient algorithms (allowing a single pass over data in some cases, instead of requiring multiple passes) and implementing classical data structures, such as doubly linked lists and queues, in functional languages.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] In mathematics, specifically in category theory, an **F -coalgebra** is a structure defined according to a functor F , with specific properties as defined below.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] For both algebras and coalgebras, a functor is a convenient and general way of organizing a signature.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] This has applications in computer science: examples of coalgebras include lazy evaluation, infinite data structures, such as streams, and also transition systems.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Just as the class of all algebras for a given signature and equational theory form a variety, so does the class of all F -coalgebras satisfying a given equational theory form a covariety, where the signature is given by F .
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] be an endofunctor on a category ${\mathcal {C}}$ .
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] of ${\mathcal {C}}$ , usually written as $(A,\alpha )$ .
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Thus the F -coalgebras for a given functor *F* constitute a category.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Consider the endofunctor $X\mapsto X\sqcup \{*\}:\mathbf {Set} \to \mathbf {Set}$ that sends a set to its disjoint union with the singleton set $\{\ast \}$ .
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] In fact, $({\overline {\mathbb {N} }},\alpha )$ is the terminal coalgebra of this endofunctor.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] More generally, fix some set A , and consider the functor $F:\mathbf {Set} \longrightarrow \mathbf {Set}$ that sends X to $(X\times A)\cup \{1\}$ .
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Then an F -coalgebra $\alpha :X\longrightarrow (X\times A)\cup \{1\}=FX$ is a finite or infinite stream over the alphabet A , where X is the set of states and $\alpha$ is the state-transition function.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Applying the state-transition function to a state may yield two possible results: either an element of A together with the next state of the stream, or the element of the singleton set $\{1\}$ as a separate "final state" indicating that there are no more values in the stream.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Special cases of practical interest include observers yielding attribute values, and mutator methods of the form $X\rightarrow X^{A_{1}\times \ldots \times A_{n}}$ taking additional parameters and yielding states.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] This decomposition is dual to the decomposition of initial F -algebras into sums of 'constructors'.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Let *P* be the power set construction on the category of sets, considered as a covariant functor.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] The *P*-coalgebras are in bijective correspondence with sets with a binary relation.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] Then coalgebras for the endofunctor *P*(*A*×(-)) are in bijective correspondence with labelled transition systems, and homomorphisms between coalgebras correspond to functional bisimulations between labelled transition systems.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] In computer science, coalgebra has emerged as a convenient and suitably general way of specifying the behaviour of systems and data structures that are potentially infinite, for example classes in object-oriented programming, streams and transition systems.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] While algebraic specification deals with functional behaviour, typically using inductive datatypes generated by constructors, coalgebraic specification is concerned with behaviour modelled by coinductive process types that are observable by selectors, much in the spirit of automata theory.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] An important role is played here by final coalgebras, which are complete sets of possibly infinite behaviours, such as streams.
[src:coinduction/f-coalgebra] The natural logic to express properties of such systems is coalgebraic modal logic.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In programming language theory, **lazy evaluation**, or **call-by-need**, is an evaluation strategy which delays the evaluation of an expression until its value is needed (non-strict evaluation) and which avoids repeated evaluations (by the use of sharing).
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is often combined with memoization, as described in Jon Bentley's *Writing Efficient Programs*.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] If so, the stored result is simply returned.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] If not, the function is evaluated, and another entry is added to the lookup table for reuse.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is difficult to combine with imperative features such as exception handling and input/output, because the order of operations becomes indeterminate.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The opposite of lazy evaluation is eager evaluation, sometimes known as strict evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Eager evaluation is the evaluation strategy employed in most programming languages.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation was introduced for lambda calculus by Christopher Wadsworth.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] For programming languages, it was independently introduced by Peter Henderson and James H.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation is used particularly in functional programming languages.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] When using delayed evaluation, an expression is not evaluated as soon as it gets bound to a variable, but when the evaluator is forced to produce the expression's value.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is fundamental in big data frameworks such as Apache Spark, where computations on distributed datasets are delayed until results are explicitly needed, allowing for execution optimizations and reduction of unnecessary processing.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation allows control structures to be defined normally, and not as primitives or compile-time techniques.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] These have the usual semantics, i.e., `ifThenElse a b c` evaluates (a), then if and only if (a) evaluates to true does it evaluate (b), otherwise it evaluates (c).
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] That is, exactly one of (b) or (c) will be evaluated.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Similarly, for `EasilyComputed || LotsOfWork`, if the easy part gives **True** the lots of work expression could be avoided.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Finally, when evaluating `SafeToTry && Expression`, if *SafeToTry* is **false** there will be no attempt at evaluating the *Expression*.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Conversely, in an eager language the above definition for `ifThenElse a b c` would evaluate (a), (b), and (c) regardless of the value of (a).
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] This is not the desired behavior, as (b) or (c) may have side effects, take a long time to compute, or throw errors.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] It is usually possible to introduce user-defined lazy control structures in eager languages as functions, though they may depart from the language's syntax for eager evaluation: Often the involved code bodies need to be wrapped in a function value, so that they are executed only when called.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation has the advantage of being able to create calculable infinite lists without infinite loops or size matters interfering in computation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The actual values are only computed when needed.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] For example, one could create a function that creates an infinite list (often called a *stream*) of Fibonacci numbers.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The calculation of the *n*-th Fibonacci number would be merely the extraction of that element from the infinite list, forcing the evaluation of only the first n members of the list.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In the function numberFromInfiniteList, the value of infinity is an infinite range, but until an actual value (or more specifically, a specific value at a certain index) is needed, the list is not evaluated, and even then, it is only evaluated as needed (i.e., only to the desired index).
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Provided the programmer is careful, the program completes normally.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell syntax, "`:`" prepends an element to a list, `tail` returns a list without its first element, and `zipWith` uses a specified function (in this case addition) to combine corresponding elements of two lists to produce a third.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In computer windowing systems, the painting of information to the screen is driven by *expose events* which drive the display code at the last possible moment.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] By doing this, windowing systems avoid computing unnecessary display content updates.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Another example of laziness in modern computer systems is copy-on-write page allocation or demand paging, where memory is allocated only when a value stored in that memory is changed.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Laziness can be useful for high performance scenarios.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] An example is the Unix mmap function, which provides *demand driven* loading of pages from disk, so that only those pages actually touched are loaded into memory, and unneeded memory is not allocated.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] MATLAB implements *copy on edit*, where arrays which are copied have their actual memory storage replicated only when their content is changed, possibly leading to an *out of memory* error when updating an element afterwards instead of during the copy operation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The number of beta reductions to reduce a lambda term with call-by-need is not larger than the number needed by call-by-value or call-by-name reduction.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Call-by-need embodies two optimizations - never repeat work (similar to call-by-value), and never perform unnecessary work (similar to call-by-name).
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also lead to reduction in memory footprint, since values are created when needed.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In practice, lazy evaluation may cause significant performance issues compared to eager evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] For example, on modern computer architectures, delaying a computation and performing it later is slower than performing it immediately .
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] This can be alleviated through strictness analysis.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also introduce memory leaks due to unevaluated expressions.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Some programming languages delay evaluation of expressions by default, and some others provide functions or special syntax to delay evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In KRC, Miranda, and Haskell, evaluation of function arguments is delayed by default.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In many other languages, evaluation can be delayed by explicitly suspending the computation using special syntax (as with Scheme's "`delay`" and "`force`" and OCaml's "`lazy`" and "`Lazy.force`") or, more generally, by wrapping the expression in a thunk.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In lazy programming languages such as Haskell, although the default is to evaluate expressions only when they are demanded, it is possible in some cases to make code more eager—or conversely, to make it more lazy again after it has been made more eager.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] This can be done by explicitly coding something which forces evaluation (which may make the code more eager) or avoiding such code (which may make the code more lazy).
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] *Strict* evaluation usually implies eagerness, but they are technically different concepts.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] However, there is an optimisation implemented in some compilers called strictness analysis, which, in some cases, allows the compiler to infer that a value will always be used.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In such cases, this may render the programmer's choice of whether to force that particular value or not, irrelevant, because strictness analysis will force strict evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell, marking constructor fields strict means that their values will always be demanded immediately.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The `seq` function can also be used to demand a value immediately and then pass it on, which is useful if a constructor field should generally be lazy.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] However, neither of these techniques implements *recursive* strictness—for that, a function called `deepSeq` was invented.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Also, pattern matching in Haskell 98 is strict by default, so the `~` qualifier has to be used to make it lazy.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In C++, the `std::ranges` library uses lazy range adaptors.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In Java, lazy evaluation can be done by using objects that have a method to evaluate them when the value is needed.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The body of this method must contain the code required to perform this evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Since the introduction of lambda expressions in Java SE8, Java has supported a compact notation for this.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The `Lazy` interface with its `eval()` method is equivalent to the `Supplier` interface with its `get()` method in the `java.util.function` library.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Each class that implements the `Lazy` interface must provide an `eval` method, and instances of the class may carry whatever values the method needs to accomplish lazy evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In the above, the variable a initially refers to a lazy integer object created by the lambda expression `() -> 1`.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Evaluating this lambda expression is similar to constructing a new instance of an anonymous class that implements `Lazy<Integer>` with an eval method returning 1.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Each iteration of the loop links a to a new object created by evaluating the lambda expression inside the loop.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Each of these objects holds a reference to another lazy object, b, and has an eval method that calls `b.eval()` twice and returns the sum.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The variable b is needed here to meet Java's requirement that variables referenced from within a lambda expression be effectively final.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] This is an inefficient program because this implementation of lazy integers does not memoize the result of previous calls to eval.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] It also involves considerable autoboxing and unboxing.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] What may not be obvious is that, at the end of the loop, the program has constructed a linked list of 11 objects and that all of the actual additions involved in computing the result are done in response to the call to `a.eval()` on the final line of code.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] This call recursively traverses the list to perform the necessary additions.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] This allows the previous example to be rewritten to be far more efficient.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] Java's lambda expressions are just syntactic sugar.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In JavaScript, lazy evaluation can be simulated by using a generator.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] You can run this example yourself by going to the Kotlin Playground.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] To verify that the program lazily loaded `isThePizzaReady` instead of initializing it beforehand as true we need to check the output of the program.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] As we can see when the program reads from `isThePizzaReady` it prints out a statement we put inside the lazy code block on line 4.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The statement on line 4 does not execute more than once.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x the `range()` function computes a list of integers.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In Python 3.x the `range()` function returns a generator which computes elements of the list on demand.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] This change to lazy evaluation saves execution time for large ranges which may never be fully referenced and memory usage for large ranges where only one or a few elements are needed at any time.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x is possible to use a function called `xrange()` which returns an object that generates the numbers in the range on demand.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The advantage of `xrange` is that generated object will always take the same amount of memory.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] From version 2.2 forward, Python manifests lazy evaluation by implementing iterators (lazy sequences) unlike tuple or list sequences.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] , the first element '0' is printed when need arises.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In the .NET framework, it is possible to do lazy evaluation using the class `System.Lazy<T>`.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] The class can be easily exploited in F# using the `lazy` keyword, while the `force` method will force the evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] There are also specialized collections like `Microsoft.FSharp.Collections.Seq` that provide built-in support for lazy evaluation.
[src:coinduction/lazy-evaluation] In C# and VB.NET, the class `System.Lazy<T>` is directly used.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] Generating and computing with streams requires lazy evaluation, either implicitly in a lazily evaluated language or by creating and forcing thunks in an eager language.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] In total languages they must be defined as codata and can be iterated over using (guarded) corecursion.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] Java provides the Stream interface under the java.util.stream namespace.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] JavaScript provides the ReadableStream, WritableStream and TransformStream interfaces.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] Python have the StreamReader and StreamWriter classes in the asyncio module.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] .NET provides the abstract class Stream which is implemented by classes such as FileStream and MemoryStream.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] In Rust a struct can implement the Read trait.
[src:coinduction/stream-abstract-data-type] There is also the Cursor struct wraps an in-memory buffer.
